result.execSummary:
The defendant Jeffrey A Harnish was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).
  • Failure to Support Child (120 Days+), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.22(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

1:37 p.m.  Defendant present in court with Atty Jeanne Zamzow.  Lisa Vanden Branden for the State of Wisconsin.  Atty Zamzow recites agreement - defendant will plea to counts 3 & 4 and counts 1 & 2 will be dismissed and read-in as well as a uncharged count from 07/05/2014 is to be dismissed and read-in.  State concurs.  Atty Zamzow concurs.  Defendant concurs.

Court goes over plea questionnaire with the defendant.  Court goes over constitutional rights with the defendant - defendant waives these rights.  Court goes over the elements of each offense.  Court instructs defendant of the maximum penalty.  Court instructs defendant regarding deportation.  (If felony) Court instructs regarding felony prohibitions.

Defendant enters a plea of NO CONTEST.  Court finds the plea is made freely, voluntarily, intelligently and understandingly.  Court finds there is a factual basis to support the plea.  Court finds the defendant guilty to counts 3 & 4 as charged.  Court orders counts 1 & 2 be dismissed and read-in.  Court dismisses the uncharged count from 2014.  Court orders the judgment of conviction be entered here today.  ADA confirms compliance with victim witness rights.  Sentencing statement by DA.  Sentencing statement by Atty Zamzow.  Statement by the defendant.

Count 3 - 1 year of Initial Confinement and 2 years of Extended Supervision, stayed and places the defendant on probation for 48 months.
